<item>
  <title>WDVV in one page</title>
  <link>https://samarthsheth.github.io/blog/posts/wdvv.html</link>
  <description><![CDATA[ 





<p>The WDVV equation is the associativity condition for the <strong>quantum product</strong> on <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?H%5E*(X)">. Stripped of context, it’s just associativity of a deformed product — but the deformation has geometric content, and the equation it satisfies turns into a recursion for Gromov–Witten invariants.</p>
<section id="the-setup" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="the-setup">The setup</h2>
<p>Fix a smooth projective variety <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?X">. Pick a basis <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?T_0,%20T_1,%20%5Cdots,%20T_m"> of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?H%5E*(X,%20%5Cmathbb%7BQ%7D)"> with <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?T_0%20=%201">. Let</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%0Ag_%7Bab%7D%20=%20%5Cint_X%20T_a%20%5Ccup%20T_b%0A"></p>
<p>be the Poincaré pairing, and let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g%5E%7Bab%7D"> be its inverse. The <strong>genus-0 Gromov–Witten potential</strong> is</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%0A%5CPhi(t)%20=%20%5Csum_%7Bn%20%5Cgeq%203%7D%20%5Csum_%7B%5Cbeta%7D%20%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Bn!%7D%20%5Clangle%20T_%7Ba_1%7D,%20%5Cdots,%20T_%7Ba_n%7D%20%5Crangle_%7B0,%20%5Cbeta%7D%5C,%20t%5E%7Ba_1%7D%20%5Ccdots%20t%5E%7Ba_n%7D%20q%5E%7B%5Cbeta%7D.%0A"></p>
</section>
<section id="the-equation" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="the-equation">The equation</h2>
<p>Write <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5CPhi_%7Babc%7D%20=%20%5Cpartial_a%20%5Cpartial_b%20%5Cpartial_c%20%5CPhi">. <strong>WDVV</strong> is:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%0A%5Csum_%7Be,%20f%7D%20%5CPhi_%7Babe%7D%5C,%20g%5E%7Bef%7D%5C,%20%5CPhi_%7Bfcd%7D%20=%20%5Csum_%7Be,%20f%7D%20%5CPhi_%7Bace%7D%5C,%20g%5E%7Bef%7D%5C,%20%5CPhi_%7Bfbd%7D%0A%5Cquad%20%5Ctext%7Bfor%20all%20%7D%20a,%20b,%20c,%20d.%0A"></p>
<p>Equivalently: the product <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?T_a%20*_t%20T_b%20=%20%5Csum_%7Be,f%7D%20%5CPhi_%7Babe%7D%5C,%20g%5E%7Bef%7D%5C,%20T_f"> is <strong>associative</strong>.</p>
</section>
<section id="why-its-true" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="why-its-true">Why it’s true</h2>
<p>There’s a map <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Coverline%7BM%7D_%7B0,4%7D%20%5Cto%20%5Coverline%7BM%7D_%7B0,0%7D%20%5Ccong%20%5Cmathrm%7Bpt%7D">, and <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Coverline%7BM%7D_%7B0,4%7D%20%5Ccong%20%5Cmathbb%7BP%7D%5E1">. The three boundary points of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Coverline%7BM%7D_%7B0,4%7D"> correspond to the three ways of splitting the four marked points <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5C%7B1,2,3,4%5C%7D"> into two pairs:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%0A%5C%7B12%20%5Cmid%2034%5C%7D,%20%5Cquad%20%5C%7B13%20%5Cmid%2024%5C%7D,%20%5Cquad%20%5C%7B14%20%5Cmid%2023%5C%7D.%0A"></p>
<p>These three boundary divisors are <em>linearly equivalent</em> in <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathrm%7BPic%7D(%5Cmathbb%7BP%7D%5E1)%20%5Ccong%20%5Cmathbb%7BZ%7D">. Pulling that linear equivalence back through the forgetful map <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Coverline%7BM%7D_%7B0,n+4%7D(X,%20%5Cbeta)%20%5Cto%20%5Coverline%7BM%7D_%7B0,4%7D"> and integrating against insertions gives WDVV.</p>
</section>
<section id="what-it-buys-you" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="what-it-buys-you">What it buys you</h2>
<p>For <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?X%20=%20%5Cmathbb%7BP%7D%5E2"> with the standard basis <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?T_0%20=%201,%20T_1%20=%20H,%20T_2%20=%20H%5E2">, WDVV with <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(a,%20b,%20c,%20d)%20=%20(1,%201,%202,%202)"> collapses to a recursion for the numbers <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?N_d"> of rational curves of degree <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?d"> through <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?3d-1"> points:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%0AN_d%20=%20%5Csum_%7Bd_1%20+%20d_2%20=%20d%7D%20N_%7Bd_1%7D%20N_%7Bd_2%7D%20%5Cleft%5B%20d_1%5E2%20d_2%5E2%20%5Cbinom%7B3d-4%7D%7B3d_1-2%7D%20-%20d_1%5E3%20d_2%20%5Cbinom%7B3d-4%7D%7B3d_1-1%7D%20%5Cright%5D.%0A"></p>
<p>This is <strong>Kontsevich’s formula</strong>. With <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?N_1%20=%201">:</p>
<table class="caption-top table">
<thead>
<tr class="header">
<th><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?d"></th>
<th>1</th>
<th>2</th>
<th>3</th>
<th>4</th>
<th>5</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr class="odd">
<td><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?N_d"></td>
<td>1</td>
<td>1</td>
<td>12</td>
<td>620</td>
<td>87,304</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>The numbers explode fast. <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?N_2%20=%201"> matches the classical fact that five points determine a unique conic; <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?N_3%20=%2012"> is harder to see classically.</p>
</section>
<section id="takeaway" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="takeaway">Takeaway</h2>
<p>WDVV is one equation. It encodes a <em>lot</em> — associativity, the boundary geometry of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Coverline%7BM%7D_%7B0,4%7D">, and counts of rational curves all at once. That economy is the appeal of the theory.</p>


</section>

 ]]></description>
